EPA chief Scott Pruitt on delaying planned directives to reduce Obama administration's emissions
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by fifteen states, its chief, Scott Pruitt, dismissed his earlier decision to delay the implementation of the former Obama administration's plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt introduced changes under his plan. It responds more quickly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
