This applies to the last date set at 1. October, when states should start complying with the 2015 regulations to reduce ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the deal by one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid "intervention with local decisions or impending economic growth."
Pruitt, who held the position of Oklahoma's state attorney general before being appointed head of the EPA, for a long time, served as a reliable opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since he settled in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industries.
The sudden turnaround Wednesday is the biggest legal failure for Pruitt's regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA's executor had exceeded his authority in an effort to delay the inclusion of the Obama administration's plan, which required oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement issued on Wednesday night, Pruitt proposed its version of the ozone standards and strengthened the EPA's commitment to cooperation with states through complex processes and the fulfilment of new standards within a given timeframe.
"Under the government of the previous administration, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and waited for it to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to a settlement and further setting up plans," said Pruitt, who in his previous position filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA.
“We do not believe in regulation by lawsuit and we take the fulfilment of the deadline seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it.”
However, the EPA statement said Pruitt could use "the option of delay and all other legally available authorities" at some point to ensure that regulation "is based on sound policy and the most accessible information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more extensive transcript of ozone rules.
The White House budget, approved last month, is seeking to delay the 2015 implementation of the rules by at least eight years.
The measure still has not passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed a coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group would not allow legal pressure.
“The turnaround in the EPA’s views – following our court battle – is an important victory for the health and safety of those 6.7 million New Yorkers and the more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution,” Schneiderman added.
New York City was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone occurs when common harmful substances discharged by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths every year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists acknowledge Pruitt's sudden change with gratitude.
"It's worrying what pressure we need to exert to change the minds of those responsible and protect the air we breathe," said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to struggle with the Trump administration’s ideological campaign to help polluters and special interests.”
