China lacks tourists.
Beijing is losing billions because of visa policy.
For decades, China has been trying to exert its influence without the use of power resources.
It spends tens of billions of dollars a year to support language schools and build universities abroad, pushing its entertainment industry into foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
Beijing is not doing well.
The state media there talks about a plan to make tourism a driving force for economic transformation and modernization.
However, the number of arrivals rose just 3.8 percent last year and roughly 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, evaluates the situation in the world's most populous country, University of Beijing's economics professor Christopher Balding, in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for itself is Chinese visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel with China, and citizens of the others must obtain a visa in advance.
At Chinese authorities in the U.S., therefore, crowds are comparable to Chinese New Year celebrations.
A visa costs 140 dollars, but if you don’t want to wait for it for hours in a queue, you have to pay 100 dollars or more for additional services.
Such restrictions build significant economic obstacles.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces the country's number of visitors by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's gross domestic product and less than one percent of all residents, was visited by 1.8 million Americans.
China often exacerbates the problem itself when it uses tourism to realize its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China restricted traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a rift around South Korea's missile defense system, the South Koreans repaid it and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw it grow by 85 percent.
All of this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the U.S. central bank, the Fed could leave China as a result of foreign trips of the Chinese to up to 190 billion dollars, while China will receive about 35 billion dollars a year as part of the sale of the currency to incoming tourists.
According to official figures on the development of the balance of payments, China had a deficit of 217 billion dollars in tourism last year, equal to 44 percent of China’s entire surplus in trade in goods.
Thus, a small number of tourists, which anxiously prevents the outflow of capital, is dealting a very painful blow.
However, the above factors are only one manifestation of more general restraint towards foreigners.
In many places in China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, less than a million foreigners lived across China.
There are more in the United States and some individual cities.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has doubled.
A number of scientific papers show that immigrants usually revive economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
You won’t find them in China.
Resolving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step that is being offered is the simplification of the visa system.
Other Asian countries, notably India and Vietnam, have recently been making great efforts to simplify and make visa procedures cheaper.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.
