Latest test results to determine the age limit of asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of tests by asylum seekers in Sweden, who have been subjected to a new method assessing their age, show that over 80 percent of people were surveyed as over the age of 18, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (RÃttsmedicinalverket) began conducting new tests earlier this year.
The aim of the method is to assess candidates more precisely in the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to determine the right age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has handed over 6880 cases for investigation, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2481 tests, carried out from mid-March to 31. July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were assessed as over the age of 18, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency concluded that the interviewee was "possible over 18 years of age."
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the interviewee was "perhaps under 18 years of age."
Tests shall be taken only if the age of the questioned person is questionable.
According to Johan GÃ¶ransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
“Compared to last month, the statistics are in the tracks and the numbers are very similar,” he told The Local.
A higher number of applicants whose age has been estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lie about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases, it was found that "the interviewed person is 18 years or older."
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases, the respondent said he would be 18 this year.
The method of determining age, which includes an X-ray of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of the knee joints, was also criticized, which is subsequently assessed by dentists and X-rayologists.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, who, among other things, deals with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age when the person went through puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we can’t determine age with precision, we shouldn’t pretend otherwise,” he told Metro.
Forensic medical agency Agency's GÃ¶ransson defended the decision in the words: "In general, it can be said that the risk of having an error of assessment of a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the person interviewed is just below the 18-year limit, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all those questioned."
