How will football's financial rules affect Neymar's move to Paris
The rules limiting the funding of European football clubs will not in any way disrupt Neymar's record-breaking transfer from Barcelona, Spain, to France's Paris-Saint Germain.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
The financial fair play rules (FFP) that UEFA introduced in 2011 stipulate that PSG will have to prove that Neymar's transfer was not funded without major losses.
Barcelona paid 222 million euros just to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
This is followed by several financial conditions for Neymar's transfer to France.
With the PSG team funded by a wealthy Qatari family that has become rich in energy sales, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already stellar football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums on the purchase of players, but on the other hand, they have to prove legal sources of income, which allows them to cover the overheads of football-related business activities.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after placing in the chair of the director of UEFA in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that are in debt in pursuit of new reinforcements ultimately cheat and risk bankruptcy if banks or owners refuse to secure them.
In 2011, the FFP rules redirected their attention from club debts to monitor their losses.
That change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovic with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spent a lot of money on players y to build a global brand - was suddenly not so profitable.
As part of the current three-year trial period, which will end in 2018, clubs can report a loss of up to 30 million euros.
And despite Platini having to leave his post in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Cheferin, is determined to advocate a ban on excessive spending.
"The FFP rules still apply and we are determined to strengthen them in the future," Andrea Traverso, who oversees compliance with FFP rules, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG has paid the amount for the redemption of Neymar in a one-time payment, it may, for accounting purposes, spread the amount for the entire duration of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to 44.4 million euros each year for five years.
The first wave of FFP's highest sanctions hit PSG in 2014 along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG have been fined 60 million euros (82 million dollars) - which were later reduced to 20 million euros - and a Champions League team reduction order to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is looking out for teams that can try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenue through companies linked to club owners.
Thus, although the Qatari company sponsors PSG once the funding exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the billing of the amount.
UEFA took a similar measure in 2014 after deciding that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to PSG was too high.
Some of Neymar's income at PSG could be paid from the 2022 FIFA World Cup Organizing Committee in Qatar, according to some reports.
However, PSG and the 2022 World Cup officials in Qatar have denied the fat that Neymat should become an ambassador for the World Cup in football and that such a manoeuvre would easily be detected by UEFA officials.
The previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to Tuesday's statement by insiders, UEFA has not launched any investigation into the transfer of Neymar to PSG.
A source wished to remain anonymous because he is not authorized to comment on the situation with PSG, The Associated Press reported.
The latest published financial statements show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of 10 million euros and a turnover of 542.4 million euro.
The financial statements for the current financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expect the arrival of Neymar will be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchandising and jersey sales.
The club expects to increase turnover by up to 30 percent from signing the contract.
The Spanish league officials, obviously concerned about the departure of one of the biggest stars, sought to thwart Neymar's departure, arguing that PSG would violate FFP rules.
"This is a clear case of 'financial doping' of both the club and the state," La Liga president Javier Teba told the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to the ownership of the PSG club by the Qatari syndicate.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's same stance on club funding.
“This is the result of ownership that has fundamentally changed the football world over the past 15 years,” Wenger said in a statement.
“Once the owner of the club becomes the state, anything is possible.
Complying with the rules of financial fair play is very difficult because the state can have different interests in the participation of such players in its club."
