Patients will have access to 'transformative' treatments for HIV prevention from September on the basis of the Supreme Court's decision to fund the drug NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to fund the probationary period after the appeals court backed the Supreme Court's decision last year, saying the NHS had funds to pay for PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by the NHS of England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
The sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018, full implementation across England will take place.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there are a sufficient number of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include gay or bisexual men, transsexual people and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics shall identify eligible participants who will sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transsexual people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GPs in the UK can also apply in their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will come to taxpayers at £10 million and NHS England signed a drug distribution contract this week after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: 'This important intervention should complement and fully work the ever-expanding and increasingly successful effort to prevent HIV.
It's another milestone in a more than thirty-year effort to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, chief executive of NAT (National Aids Trust) said: 'We are witnessing a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and at risk to patients, it will offer the possibility of a change in the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, chief executive of Terrence Higgins Trust said: 'The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure its availability to each patient.
We now have the PrEP test drug at our disposal and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10 000 people at risk of contracting HIV.'
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: 'The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start the tests as soon as possible across the country, protecting people who are exposed to HIV and together end the spread of HIV in society.'
