Italians toughen up fighting NGO rescue ships with immigrants on board
Italy has announced that it will prevent the arrival of NGO rescue ships arriving on the coast of Italy with immigrants from the Mediterranean unless the NGO signs new rules regulating their operations.
"If the NGO does not sign the new rules of conduct, it will be difficult for us to imagine that they could continue their operations," Interior Minister Marco Minniti said in an interview with Turin daily La Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities seized the ship of the German rescue organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion of human trafficking, which significantly eases illegal immigration.
The rescue organization, which is operating for the first year, declined to comment on the matter on the grounds of allegations by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosios.
“For us, the number one priority is to save people’s lives. We are therefore very sorry that we cannot currently operate in rescue zones," the organization said in a statement on social media.
“We can only comment on all the current accusations after gathering all the information and evaluating the situation.”
Italian authorities have been tracking the Iuventa ship of the Jugend Rettet organization since October.
Her crew is suspected of having transported immigrants on the ship, which was handed over directly to them by human traffickers, repeatedly.
At least one meeting occurred, according to the plaintiff's file, reportedly only 1.3 miles off the coast of Libya. The meeting was published by Italian media.
The ship's crew is suspected of breaking the law and bypassing the Italian coast guard, who oversees rescue operations in the area - out of humanitarian enthusiasm, rather than anything else.
The Code of Conduct establishes the presence of an Italian police officer on board ships such as Iuventa to monitor activities.
Only three of the nine non-governmental nonprofits involved in rescue operations have so far agreed to adhere to the code: Save The Children, Malta's MOAS and Spain's Pro-Activa Open Arms.
The latter organization said Thursday that the new rules were not necessary but acceptable because they did not represent any "substantial change or obstacle" in terms of rescue operations.
The adoption of the new code of conduct was also rejected by the organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF), which is the winner of the Nobel Prize.
Minniti, meanwhile, has said that the sharp drop in immigrants in recent weeks, which has been disembarking in Italy as part of rescue operations, suggests that efforts to strengthen patrols off the coast of Libya and cooperation with local mayors bears fruit.
"In recent days, we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
It also revealed plans for further negotiations, which will take place this month with the mayors of Libya on the economic development initiative, as well as with representatives of Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in hopes of reaching Europe.
