Lavender from Provence threatens climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the south-eastern France region, but is now threatened by climate change.
Lavender is declining due to dry climates and harmful insects, causing dismay on the faces of researchers and farmers seeking solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM in Provence, said: "Growing lavender in Provence is at risk because in the last few years this plant has been exposed to climate change, which brings with it less rainfall in the spring and autumn.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
Cicadas and grasshoppers that transmit micro-bacteria, which thrive in dry climates, are also to blame for this."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender attracts tourists, and the oil that is made from them is an important component of perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: "Instead of long and beautiful flowers, smaller, undeveloped and often weak plants grow.
The amount of oil derived from these lavenders is, of course, less.”
A possible solution may be more efficient water distribution and slowing down the evaporation of water from the soil, but also spraying lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding more species resistant to dry weather.
