At first glance, it looks like a statue, however scary.
The researchers have now uncovered the findings of the first findings of an amazing creature about the size of a rhino, whose perfectly preserved remains - which experts have called 'Mona Lisa of Dinosaurs' - was found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such a high extent that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of his scaly skin and said the dinosaur had a 'problematic past'.
A paper in the journal Current Biology said it was 'the best-preserved some of the dinosaur's ever found and one of the best dinosaur species in the world.
The fossil is a new species of the family Nodosauridae. Dinosaurus lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition literally shocked the researchers, who described him in the words of 'really remarkable'.
The armored white-eater is, according to National Geographic, the best preserved fossil of its kind.
Behind the find is Shawn Funk, who uncovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling at the Suncor Millennium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across something that looked like a foreign object and decided to explore it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to uncover an animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1100 kg.
After the work is complete, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
'Just narrow your eyes a little and you'll believe he's asleep,' said work manager Caleb Brown and the naturalist of the Royal Tyrrell Museum where the animal is on display.
“It will surely go down in history as one of the most beautiful and preserved species of the dinosaur – the Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs.”
By studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered in tingling and resembled a walking tank - was in all likelihood facing a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a masking system that many of today's animals use.
Experts say this has allowed him to blend better with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The masking system suggests it was a favorite food for larger dinosaurs.
Reports of the 110-million-year-old dinosaur family Nodosauridae first appeared in a newspaper in May. It is currently available for inspection at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers gave him the name Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who, along with the team, spent more than 7000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists document the patterns and shape of scales and tingling all over the body.
They revealed a method of camouflage commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this camouflage effect is common in nature, the researchers' findings are surprising because Borealopelta's size far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
It is therefore possible that the dinosaur was so many predators that evolution preferred masking to confrontation in survival.
Many contemporary animals with camouflage - such as deer, zebra and or armadillo - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to literally fight for its outlived.
“The prediction of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur illustrates the danger posed by predators during the Cretaceous period,” Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that dinosaur skin probably had a reddish-brown coloration.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for more insights into his life, including the preserved stomach content, to track down his last meal.
He believes the dinosaur fell into the river after his death and was carried into the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
In the Alberta region at the time, the climate was the same as in present-day Florida, and the rivers and oceans stretched farther inland than they are today.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin while also being preserved in three dimensions and we can see its original size,” Brown said.
“For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as it did in the time of the chalk.
You don't have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; you just need to narrow your eyes a little, and it seems like he's just asleep.'
In the Cretaceous period, huge teropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, were walking on the Earth, moving on two legs.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - the Tyrannosaurus rex - lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been the favorite prey of his equally fearsome ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5-meter-long monster with a weight of over 6 tons.
The researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe the body of Borealopelt was washed up into the sea after being mummified in mud.
Behind the find is Shawn Funk, who uncovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling at a Suncor Millennium mine near Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including leather and armor, which is additionally complete from muzzle to hips.
