How did one activist learn the answer to the question: ‘Whose Streets?’
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook her entire body.
The day after she arrived in New York, with a native of St. Louis sat on a bed in an Airbnb room and went through Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across the contribution of a high school student.
"The police have just shot the 18-year-old, whose body is still lying in the street," it said.
She was surprised that no one else had written this post to her, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
User @TheePharoah constantly retweeted her wall posts.
Rapper from St. Louis posted on Twitter his posts about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old young man who was shot by a white-skinned police officer in the city of Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying lifeless on the street, from where no one took him even after four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put down her phone to return to him in the evening, watching tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
She watched photos of police tapes and screaming people. One of the men claimed to be the victim's father and held a sign in his hand with the words "Ferguson police killed my unarmed son"!
She watched the live reports - one of the police officers stood in front of a group of protesters, holding a leash in his hand and a barking dog at the other end.
In another video, another police officer, as she stated, held a gun in his hand, with which he was aiming at the crowd and yelling, "I'm going to kill you all... animals."
"That's not normal," Ferrell said to herself.
"This is not the kind of murder we've been used to and that we can call normal.
I could feel the goose bumps all over my body.
“I was angry and I cried.”
She immediately booked a return flight and traveled home the next day.
After landing at 23:00, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided to head to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is described in a new documentary, "Whose Streets?", which will be released in cinemas on August 11.
It's a story about survival and protests, love and resistance, the power and resentment told from the perspective of people living in the community who take to the streets and demand answers.
On her way to Ferguson, Ferrell introduced a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral jersey and the same floral headband - about a topic they had discussed many times before - "about the experience with blacks."
“Do you remember when I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?”
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old youth and that's not right."
"It wasn't an option for me not to take her with me," Ferrell said later.
“Today’s events are the climax... that has occurred in the past.
She had to know and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
It needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but at the same time it had to know the difference between different layers of experience with black people and what we need to do to get free.
Despite the fact that I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism firsthand, she is no different from another black child-woman.
I feel that if I protected her from this experience, I would just hurt her.”
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop of the South Florissant Road was across from the police department, which became the base of activists who were expecting the words of Officer Darren Wilson about his eventual involvement in the incident.
Here, Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing food for others.
Together they prepared food for the bags and helped to distribute it to the Protestants.
A new type of activism slowly began to be born in Ferrell's eyes.
"My activism was turned upside down after August 9," Ms Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural.”
A few weeks later, Ferrell met the documentary's later co-director, Sabaah Folayan, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "only document" the ongoing events.
Ferrell, however, thought, "Are you working on a documentary or trying to find a story that could be used?"
Such a type of skepticism penetrated the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to profit from pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview: "We have heard that the voices of people who are born and grow up in Ferguson are very often neglected and that's what we wanted to change."
Folayan has already established a collaboration with co-director Damon Davis, who is a respected local artist who deals with the subject of prisoners on death row.
His participation in the project also involved Ferrell and, along with six other locals, who were followed by the "Whose Streets" team in the years following the assassination of Brown.
"Nobody speaks for us in this document, but it's our testimony," Davis said.
"That was important to me - how these people would be represented - because I would be represented in the same way."
While the aim of the documentary was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in trying to portray that the movement "is not about a savior leader, but about bringing the community closer together," Ms Folayan said - it turned out that she was the most open to participating in filmmaking.
The documentary “Whose Streets?” describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell’s life, for example, how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face at the thought of the first moment she watched the final version of the documentary.
"But I understand that in order to do this work and humanize the blacks, I have to open up."
In addition, Ferrell's story highlights the role of the eccentric black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders - who created a campaign under #BlackLivesMatter in response to the killing of teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 on social media - call themselves weirdos.
"Black eccentric women in leadership positions ultimately stand behind the preservation of the movement," Ms Ferrell said, "because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must endure the weight of these events."
Folayan agrees with that statement, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a large number of eccentric black women."
However, she insists that "this is not a mere affirmative matter" and Ferrell is not the main heroine of the documentary because of her views.
"She was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
"that she's on the front lines is no coincidence, because life at these intersections in the skin of a black strange woman is dangerous.
You can feel the rush of energy in front of the screen.”
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, the cameras of television stations have vacated their positions, but heavy racial bonds between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year probation for blocking the highway during demonstrations.
The socially political atmosphere in the area she calls home described as "a mess."
Still, she continues her quest, which she has committed to since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
The only thing we have to lose is our chains.”
