A Becoming Resemblance: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery is located several faces of different skin tones - white, black and dark - hung from the ceiling on the wires. Each of them seemed to fall out of the previous one's eye.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from swabs from the mouth and hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, launched on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, computer science and art, and Manning - a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before his departure from the post of president of the United States.
The algorithmic DNA analysis of Manning's DNA and the use of 30 portraits to illustrate what a man with this genotype would look like was created by Dewey-Hagborg's razor-sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on DNA malleability - as well as many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken since her youth that she considers herself a woman. She was sentenced in 2013 on the basis of 20 indictments, including violations of six spy laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photos were taken by prison staff. Only one lower-quality black-and-white photograph leaked to the public, on which Manning, visibly concerned, is sitting in the driver's seat in a platinum blonde wig, which she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project of Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic items - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They were planning an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to complete the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained on the occasion of the opening of the new exhibition.
However, visits and photographs were not allowed, so they turned to Chelsea asking if she would be interested in DNA portraits.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, who presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
President Obama actually asked for Manning's release a few days after the comics were released, which was a welcome change after several excruciating years spent in a Kansas military prison.
It is indeed interesting that the exhibition is taking place just as Donald Trump is waging war on people seeking to disclose government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to incite grudges with his tweets in areas he should support.
In response to a question about this special timing, Dewey-Hagborg said "everything is happening for a reason."
Under the statement of the artist on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter “i” in the surname is dotted with the heart) after the end of “self-feeding factionalism, which is based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.”
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of the letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the sophisticated scientific dictionary of the artist), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we are.
“I hope that people will take away from this, that our genome doesn’t care who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,” said Dewey-Hagborg. Her work Spurious Memories from 2007 on video can also be seen.
“DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them.”
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the above graphic novel.
She depicts Manning emerging in the manner of King Kong from the United States Displinary Barracks prison with a megaphone in her hand.
"As soon as they stop you from speaking, they will win," it says.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibition - which was predicted in the comics - but when it does, she will be greeted in the center of the room with her masks, her own genomic portraits, lined up as a crowd of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm high statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"They were placed on the walls in the past, but this time I wanted them to make a sense of crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of mass movement, which takes the form of Chelsea and frees it.”
