Startups that will help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but did not find adequate research.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even deceptive.
And yet she promised the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust throughout the process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of Madison Reed, an e-commerce company based in San Francisco that employs 75 people.
She asked for help from outside.
New human resources startups are constantly emerging on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intention of measuring employee obligations, startups allow companies to make quick voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, and offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow informants to bypass supervisors and contact the director directly.
“There are tools in the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Glint, a Reedwood City-based startup.
Errett said she has gained more awareness of what her employees think and feel in three years thanks to Glint.
In addition to rapid surveys and voting specific teams, Glint offers a company temperature map and a cursory overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of managers with a low rating - allowing the user to work on the remedy.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to take care of the culture of the work environment - in case they become another Uber - which is buffeted by scandals after a former employee posted on his blog a post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys presents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let's Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance sector can exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
The startup Convercent of Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw little increase in interest and activity at the start of the year, just before Uber's scandals.
Nearly 600 Convercent clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has also adopted under its wing.
Similar to Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable “lightning” surveys, collect confidential information in real-time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the issue, the complaints shall be sent directly to the Board of Directors.
"The Court of Public Opinion has empowered regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and chief executive of the startup Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical conduct - and if regulators do not intervene - it may face costly consequences as a result of boycotting customers, staff exhaustion or legal proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employee awareness of corporate policies and procedures and ensure an easy way to contact corporate leadership.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to trace the phone number or email to the company management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful resolution.
It was often a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, general counsel of Ruby Tuesday, according to which there was previously no reliable way of monitoring employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, it is ensured to quickly detect and resolve problems that have never previously reached managers sitting in offices, miles away from a real-life solution to complaints - for example, discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"It's coming to a holistic, overall view of the experience of employees," said Vitrano, who run Ruby Tuesday's group overseeing risk management.
“At the same time, we protect shareholders from lawsuits by employees.”
The companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron's downfall in the abuse of employee ethics rights, Quinlan said.
But it was only when social media “shone a light on the whole thing” that companies began to realize that in the online world they could not simply hide their skeletons in their closet.
“Before people started using technology to track ethics, people were relying on the faith,” Quinlan said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which the company pays regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity endorsed by the brave capital investors who have supported both startups.
Convercent collected a total of $10 million as part of his February campaign from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually took home a capital of $47 million.
Glint earned $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and earned $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of societies, culture and venture capital.
The growing number of research clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, not the main advantage of high salaries and interesting projects.
Employees want to perceive that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
“If people are happy in their work, they perceive that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the success of the company,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits from both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money if companies thrive and companies thrive if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool emerges in the market that ensures employee engagement and commitment to the company, it’s no wonder that there are plenty of investors who will support this effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is pointless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The reality is that once the company asks for feedback from its employees, there can be major changes.
And if change doesn't happen quickly - in the worst case at all - it can cause disappointment and lack of interest to employees.
"Once you ask for 4000 opinions, you need to be prepared for 4000 conversations," said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, which has witnessed many companies that have relied too heavily on the data itself.
“Since once you don’t finish things, the staff will start to wonder, ‘Did they even hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, then why should I care?'" "
Madison Reed, which now conducts a survey of employees on a regular basis every month, can solve the problem within a day thanks to Glint, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and communication quality, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start training communications to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the industry in the long run, which is known for frequent layoffs.
“If you’re not trying to create a transparent work environment, employees won’t trust you,” Vitrano said.
"And once you start losing employees, you'll lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt.”
