Facebook plans to have more thorough fact-checking to limit the number of fake news
Facebook will send more potentially fake articles to review third parties and display findings under original posts in an effort to combat so-called "fake news," the largest social network said Thursday.
The company writes on its website that it will start using updated machine learning to detect possible hoaxes that will send to third parties for verification and potentially display the survey results under the original posts.
Facebook has been described as one of the main sources of fake news, and many believe these unconfirmed reports have influenced last year's election of the president of the United States.
There are political debates about the whole issue in Europe. French voters are inundated with an avalanche of fake news about the May presidential election, and Germany plans to impose a fine on the social media network in advance of the September election if it does not urgently remove angry posts.
Facebook said in a statement issued in Germany on Thursday that it was planning to launch a new feature of the control of fake news in the U.S., France, the Netherlands and Germany.
"In addition to displaying third-party verified reports, people are asking for more content to be better informed and to be able to make the right decision about what they can share," Sara Su, Facebook's product news manager, said in a blog post.
She added that Facebook is continuing to test the "related articles" feature and is also working on other changes to reduce the number of fake news.
Creating a graphic novel: a story about A Castle in England
The small castle of Scottey Castle recently played the lead role in the music video of the band Squeeze and was also sheltered by Margaret Thatcher during the 70's and 80's of the last century.
Scottey, however, witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history from his cosy spot by the Bewl River in Kent, Britain, that inspired the curly Jamie Rhodes of the York County - known for his fondness for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
“The sight of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me,” Rhodes says with a serious face.
“When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection.”
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the life of families who lived at Scottey Castle from the Middle Ages until the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes's first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by British Library documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on the letter written by a double agent in the 70's who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbs-up!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love the archives!”
For someone so fascinated by the old papers, the support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to dwell in the castle for almost four months is almost like a dream. (“To tell you the truth, I’ve extended my stay a little.”)
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian “new” castle, browsing through the archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of the hyena on the wall and the bottles that had been dumped in a ditch for centuries.
He walked the property and explored the ruins of the old castle, speaking with the gardeners, gardeners and occasionally also with artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
At night, he “sipped whiskey and wrote.”
Scotney's intimate history is a relatively unknown, as the National Trust gained access to the documents only in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the scene ten years later, the staff were beginning to penetrate the archives that Rhodes had described in words, like “the aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands around with the words, ‘Put it in the attic.’”
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps depicting property: "You might think the dispute over land is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were tugging at birch.
Stop it people! "
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Uprising of 1381.
"I found a record of the 1380 Castle Rebellion, which was in the book called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area and I thought the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe it’s connected in the end.”
The other stories are firmly linked to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who reportedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was only discovered several years after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes's favorite family is Darrell's: "I was intrigued by the male generation - the men of that time were always indebted and spent money on things they couldn't afford.
The different generations of the Darrell family dealt with this by taking rich or old mistresses - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to hang out the heads of the heirs. "
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes is searching for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stage in the Finnish wilderness, where he soaked up inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former early 20th-century sanatorium that was swallowed up by nature.
But it's a special place for Scottey.
“I was sad when I left,” he said.
“I was like, ‘Now to get the hell back to real life.’”
