Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300 000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to produce immune cells that promote gut resistance.
Head of study dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilt to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the body's tolerance in the stomach of mice with a particular bacteria.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to create cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have found a connection between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that promote body tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells."
At the same time, he suggested that if it turns out that the same applies to humans, then the combination of the bacteria L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher dr. As part of her study of a certain kind of body tolerance-promoting immune cells, Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice kept separately lacked cells.
She inferred that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally dwell in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of the mice were tested by the DNA sorting method, and the researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells that lacked by the second group of mice.
Mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome - so they didn't develop this kind of immune cells - were given the bacterium L. reuteri - and created immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers have grown L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that have been kept in isolation.
Immune cells evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mouse's diet, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, after splitting the dose of tryptophan, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if the by-products of tryptophan from the bacterium L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in the genes related to tryptophan have been detected in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan said: “Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammatoryness of the inner surface of the intestines.
The potentially high level of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase the cell population."
