A British inventor uses a microchip in his hand to unlock the car and house with a wave
The British inventor became the first person in the country with a microchip injected into the body. With a simple wave of his hand, he can unlock the door from the house and office and even start the car.
Thirty-three-year-old Steven Northam has had a small chip implanted between his thumb and index finger and currently offers the same service through his company BioTeq to companies and individuals who want to make their lives easier with technology.
The procedure of implantation and compliance with treatments are supervised by dr. Geoff Watson, an anesthesiologist at Royal Hampshire County Hospital in Winchester.
The technology works on the same principle as microchips implanted with dogs and cats, and the entire procedure lasts 30 seconds.
Northam's company also offers a door and car lock replacement service, compatible with the microchip. The price of one castle is £300.
The married father of one child has integrated the technology into his house and his BMW Z4 car, which he starts with a simple wave of his hand.
White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry last month came to $24,000, according to Navy records released by the TIME weekly.
The green white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the 17 program. July at the White House, which was a showcase of U.S. design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials have looked at a product show from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was on display next to a yacht from Maine, a Wisconsin fire truck and a fork-shaped forklift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and applied for the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - the helicopter management unit - said.
"I wanted to make sure that you were aware of such a significant event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his supervisor, the deputy commander of the Navy for Aviation the day before the event began.
The report suggested that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn 17. July at approximately 7:00 a.m. on the occasion of the parade, the beginning of which is scheduled for 15:00 and will remain in place until the entire site is fully cleared, which was planned between 18:00 and 21:00.
The email further stated that if there is a delay in departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be dispatched for the return flight due to the working hours regulations.
The original crew remained on the scene that evening along with the helicopter and along with them a unit of security personnel.
It was not apparent from the records - obtained by the weekly TIME - whether the second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prevents civil servants from using government property for political purposes.
The records suggest that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this Regulation.
"We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was fine," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," the deputy commander wrote back.
This “Made in America” show was designated an official event by the White House, and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political overtones.
In his participation in the event, the president advocated health reform, which passed through the Senate and spoke of an effort to keep government regulations at bay.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane was driving in the background at his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ showcase, which has introduced products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, deputy press secretary.
The crews of the HMX-1 helicopter often train landings in the Washington and South Lawn areas, rehearsing any possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump participated in the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the crew's current training, a state official said.
The helicopter unit flew another eleven hours as part of the "non-presidential support missions" on the same day.
The White House said no other props had been paid for with taxpayers' money.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in any way in negotiations to issue a helicopter at South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights, and the exact cost in connection with the show is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017 is the DoD's expenses for VH-3D 24 $380 per flight hour.
The unit's records indicate a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below the stated amount.
"To state taxpayers' costs based on estimates for reimbursement of expenses is very misleading," Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual cost.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, compensation for DoD expenses does not include personnel costs, but include fuel price, maintenance and contractual costs.
The then White House press secretary, Sean Spicer, advocated the use of a helicopter for the purpose of the show.
"The idea of the show, which is taking place this week, is to introduce products produced in the U.S.," Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state, and that they provide work to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military installations, in the production of which countless American citizens are involved.
This is to be remembered.”
It is unclear if Trump, during his rounds at South Lawn, was also looking at a helicopter. The only thing that can be said with certainty is that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump reached out to a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I own three of them myself."
