Police dogs trained in Most by helicopter overflight
Dogs specializing in the search for explosives and search dogs were rehearsed helicopter overflights at Lake Most today.
The police dog must not be timid and afraid of flying, said Petr Tomášek, the head of the police cynologists of the Ústí Region.
The training of a police dog lasts about two years.
At Most, both adult trained dogs and those who were just going through the training practiced.
In addition to standard training, in which they were to detect sharp samples of explosives around the lake and search for the lost figurehead, all 12 animals had to board a helicopter and fly over the lake.
The main purpose of the exercise is to test the dogs in the helicopter.
So that immediately what the helicopter lands, the dog can go to work so that he does not have a problem with the helicopter journey.
"A helicopter lands, the dog goes and immediately searches," Tommy said.
A dog that is restless or unable to start working immediately along the helicopter journey is retired from training.
"Most of the time, the dog handlers keep them, for example, in the garden," Tomášek added.
The police have 76 dogs with various specializations in the Ústí Region.
German shepherds prevail, but there are also increasing sheepdogs of Belgium.
The handler takes care of it from the puppy.
"He raises it himself, prepares it for a service that the dog will do for us," Tommy added.
The animal undergoes repeated veterinary examinations, which can detect possible health handicaps.
If the dog is healthy and inconspicuous, it passes the first exams in 20 months.
"He is getting into a sharp hit around two and a half to three years," Tommy added.
The length of the service with the police depends on the health of the dog.
They usually serve up to eight to ten years.
They usually live with their dog handlers.
