According to the United Nations, Afghan democracy relies on women in politics
The election can only be credible if all members of society, including women, attend, a U.N. representative in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, a senior U.N. Auxiliary Mission official, said hundreds of women are participating in local council elections, three women are running for the post of vice president, and more than 30 percent of the newly registered voters are women.
"The role of women cannot be overlooked," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be fully representative and credible if women participate in them, as well as all related processes related to the election.
Local and presidential elections in Afghanistan are held on April 5.
The Taliban have made several threats against the electoral process that are moving international combat activity to the other track.
In this year's elections, for the first time ever, a democratically elected government hands over its power to the next government peacefully.
Haysom said the strong role of women would strengthen Afghanistan's democracy.
The Afghan Independent Election Commission said that of the total 3.6 million registered voters, 1.2 million are women.
The unique brewery brews beer again.
For a good beer in the resurrected brewery.
The enthusiasm and honesty of the new owners returned to life a few years ago the brewery in Lobč u Mšena.
The brewery, first commemorated in 1586, has a Renaissance core and was rebuilt into a steam-trained operation in the 19th century.
It was followed by years of prosperity, when the brewery was famous mainly for its dark beers.
Unfortunately, during the Second World War, production was stopped and in 1984 the brewery was nationalized.
Since then, the buildings have served the state farm.
The work of destruction was completed by the owners of the brewery after 1989.
The abandoned area was devastated and dismantled into building material.
In 2007, however, a new hope shone in the form of new owners, architects Jana and Pavel Prouz.
They began to repair the buildings with the utmost respect for the spirit of the building and every detail.
They have carefully devoted themselves and are dedicated to the study of archival materials, trying to preserve the original materials and building elements.
The brewery has the same form as in the 19th century, when its golden era began.
Their work was awarded by the brewery’s declaration as a cultural monument by the Ministry of Culture and the construction became part of the European Industrial Heritage Trails.
In 2015 they also renewed the tradition of brewing beer.
If you want to taste great Lobeč beer in the picturesque landscape of Kokořínsko, visit the bar in the brewery area.
When brewing beer, they use Kokořín water springing in a protected landscape area, malt from the Lobeč fields and Žatec hops.
In the bar you will taste traditional light lager, but also dark beers and specials.
And do not miss the tour of the brewery, it takes place on Saturday and Sunday at noon and at half past two.
