Get to know the plant with one click.
The new free application Pl@ntNet will help students with the creation of herbari and ordinary plant lovers.
When they wonder what kind of plant they just came across on a walk, this app will advise them.
All they will have to do is photograph the plant, and the application itself will recognize what kind it is.
The new application, which is available for both iOS and Android, was presented on Tuesday by representatives of the CEEV Center for Ethics and Environmental Education in Bratislava’s Mountain Park as part of the Secret Life of the City project.
The project also involved pupils from 50 Czech and Slovak schools, who with teachers photographed and added plants from their surroundings to the application database.
The newly created French app is free to download on the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of French programmers was to make as many people as possible contribute to the application with their images, thereby increasing the number of plants that the application can recognize.
"Even children who keep a tablet or mobile phone in their hands can go out into the forest," said Ivana Poláčková, the coordinator of the project.
Based on a sufficiently high-quality photo of the flower, leaf or fruit of the plant, the application can recognize its name in a few seconds, which it then assigns in Czech and Slovak under the photo.
The French allowed us to translate the application into Slovak and Czech in the project The Secret Life of the City.
It is therefore welcome for users to contribute a picture of a plant that is not yet present in the database after creating an account for the application.
"The French will evaluate whether it is beneficial and then add it to the database," Poláčková said.
